          "body": "The narrator inserts a parenthetical in verse 3 that is decisive for reading everything that follows: 'Now the man Moses was very humble, more than any man who was on the face of the earth.' The parenthesis explains Moses's silence. He does not respond to the attack. He does not marshal his credentials, cite his track record, or appeal to God on his own behalf. His silence is not cowardice or incompetence; it is the posture of the meek — those who do not defend themselves because they trust the vindication of God. The Hebrew *anav* (humble, meek, afflicted) carries the connotation of the one who has been brought low and has accepted that lowness before God, who consequently finds God's power operative on his behalf (cf. Psalm 37:11; Isaiah 57:15). This is not merely a biographical footnote. The narrator places it here because it is the hermeneutical key to everything that follows in verses 4-9: God's defense of Moses is so vigorous precisely because Moses offered none. Howard Hendricks observed that the man who is least interested in protecting his own reputation is the man God most completely vindicates — Numbers 12 is the paradigm case."
